<subSubSection lastPageId="253" lastPageNumber="254" pageId="252" pageNumber="253" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="252.[140,1108,1187,1460]" pageId="252" pageNumber="253">
As currently defined, the 
<taxonomicName box="[429,547,1223,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="252" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Noctuidae</taxonomicName>
include only those groups with a trifid hindwing venation (
<bibRefCitation author="Lafontaine JD &amp; Fibiger M" box="[253,584,1258,1285]" pageId="252" pageNumber="253" pagination="610 - 635" refId="ref253220" refString="Lafontaine JD, Fibiger M (2006) Revised higher classification of the Noctuoidea (Lepidoptera). Th e Canadian Entomologist 138: 610 - 635." type="journal article" year="2006">Lafontaine and Fibiger 2006</bibRefCitation>
), to the exclusion of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[865,967,1258,1284]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="252" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Erebidae</taxonomicName>
, which were formerly included here. Most Noctuoidea species of economic concern fall in this group, such as the cutworms, armyworms and earworms. Th ere are about 8,000 named species of 
<taxonomicName box="[260,378,1363,1389]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="252" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Noctuidae</taxonomicName>
globally, reaching their greatest diversity in temperate regions, particluarly grasslands and steppe habitats. Approximately 2,500 noctuid species occur in North America; 643 are reported herein from AB.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="252.[140,1108,1506,1672]" box="[140,305,1506,1530]" pageId="252" pageNumber="253">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[140,305,1506,1530]" italics="true" pageId="252" pageNumber="253">
63.1. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boisduval" authorityYear="1828" box="[201,305,1506,1530]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="252" pageNumber="253" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Plusiinae">Plusiinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="252.[140,1108,1506,1672]" lastBlockId="253.[140,1108,167,404]" lastPageId="253" lastPageNumber="254" pageId="252" pageNumber="253">
A group of primarily medium-sized (
<quantity box="[564,694,1539,1566]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="252" pageNumber="253" unit="mm" value="40.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="30.0">30–50 mm</quantity>
wingspan) moths with many colorful and attractive species. Many have metallic marks on the forewings, and some are diurnal flower visitors. Th e subfamily is defined by the quadrifid hindwing venation and lashed eyes. Th e larvae of most species are semi-loopers with a reduced number of prolegs. Th ey feed on the foliage of a wide variety of plants, and several (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mc Dunnough" authorityYear="1944" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Trichoplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="253" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="253" pageNumber="254">Trichoplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp.) are important agricultural pests.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="253.[140,1108,167,404]" pageId="253" pageNumber="254">
There are approximately 400 species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boisduval" authorityYear="1828" box="[626,728,237,263]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="253" pageNumber="254" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Plusiinae">Plusiinae</taxonomicName>
in the world, centered in temperate habitats in the northern hemisphere. Approximately 80 species in about 24 genera occur in North America; 41 species are known from AB. Th e North American species have been revised by 
<bibRefCitation author="McDunnough JH" box="[393,660,343,370]" pageId="253" pageNumber="254" pagination="175 - 232" refId="ref256739" refString="McDunnough JH (1944 b) Revision of the North American genera and species of the phalaenid subfamily Plusiinae. Memoirs of the Southern California Academy of Sciences 2: 175 - 232." type="journal article" year="1944">McDunnough (1944b)</bibRefCitation>
and more recently by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lafontaine JD &amp; Poole RW" pageId="253" pageNumber="254" refId="ref253465" refString="Lafontaine JD, Poole RW (1991) Noctuoidea: Noctuidae: Plusiinae. Fasc. 25.1. In: Dominick RB, Ferguson DC, Franclemont JG, Hodges RW, Munroe EG (Eds) Th e moths of America north of Mexico. Wedge Entomological Research Foundation, Washington, D. C., 182 pp." type="book" year="1991">
Lafontaine and 
<collectingRegion box="[140,202,378,404]" country="United Kingdom" name="Poole" pageId="253" pageNumber="254">Poole</collectingRegion>
(1991)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
